	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				First of all... if you end up with thousands in stolen platinum, just trading it to a frind won't get you off the hook with VI, they can track that information, I know from experience.<BR>
<BR>
It's printed in the EULA that taking advantage of exploits and bugs in the game are prohibited, if you don't agree with that, then you DO NOT AGREE with the EULA, and therefore, you SHOULD NOT play the game, period.<BR>
<BR>
Taking advantage of such exploits and bugs ruins the real fun and experience for the rest of us who want to play the game the way it is supposed to be played.<BR>
<BR>
If you don't agree with that, then cancel your account right now and burn all your game CD's, you do not deserve to play the game.<BR>
<BR>
Secondly, Perma Banning involves Credit Card and personal information which VI kdeeps on file.<BR>
<BR>
The tactic described by Paynefold below could work, but changing ISP's won't do much good, as VI can track a User to a specific terminal.  They tracked me down back in January after my brother hacked my former Guild Leader's account, after she and I had a rough falling out over Leadership when she took a 3 month leave of absence late last year.  <BR>
<BR>
My brother got her account Password from someone she gave it too years back, and he stole all her SK's armor and put it on my account, he was using his own computer in his room when he did it.  However, VI tracked the hacking to my house and contacted me directly on my own terminal while I was playing... <BR>
<BR>
Funny thing is, I was out of town the weekend my brother did it and VI pinned it on me.  To make it even more ironic, I had just petitioned about the stolen armor, wanting to know where the hell it came from.  I even told the Senior GM who was &quot;interrogating&quot; me that I didn't want it and to give it back to her.<BR>
<BR>
Basically, he didn't want to listen to me and just snapped his fingers and I was out.  VI told me they knew the hacking happened at my house regardless of what computer it happened on, to them it looked like it was all the same computer (I'm on a LAN with a DSL Router) and since the account involved in the theft was on my credit card, so they perma banned my account, but not me specifically.<BR>
<BR>
To ban me specifically, they would red flag my credit information and everytime someone would try to set up a new account with my credit card VI would deny it and turn it down. <BR>
<BR>
Ok.. but say someone wanted to use a flagged credit card but a different name then their own... Well, by law VI is required to verify the name with the credit company to ensure this person is allowed to use the credit card.  You would think this would flag people with stolen cards though, but it doesn't work that way. Someone with a stolen card could easily sign the name that is on the card. <BR>
<BR>
But with VI, all the registration and payment is done online, there is no signature required for the credit card number, just VI's faith that the person signing up is the owner of the card, if the name is different then the credit agency who distribute's the card is contacted for verification.  <BR>
<BR>
It's pretty much done that way for all online based credit transactions, if the name in the Ship To area is different then that on the card, or the name on the registration is different then that on the card, then the credit agency is supposed to be contacted before billing is allowed.<BR>
<BR>
Believe me, VI will keep track of someone they have perma banned.<BR>
<BR>
I fought the banning of my account, since the action that resulted in my account banning took place while I was out of town.  My brother didn't even have the password to my account, he hacked that while I was gone.  So I fought VI over it for nearly three months, I even threatened a Law Suit and went to talk it over with a number of lawyers, until VI sent me a list of Sony's law dog's and told me to have my lawyer contact them.<BR>
<BR>
Heck, I wish it didn't have to happen to me that way... my brother and I have even since had a major falling out and we haven't spoken to each other since.  He had done other things as well to incur my wrath towards him.  <BR>
<BR>
I am posting with an anonymous email so those who were involved in my brother's hacking won't get too upset about reading about it here, and I won't name who the person in question is that my brother hacked, other then to say that I am sorry he did it and I am sorry that the GM's wouldn't listen to me and refused to return your armor.<BR>
<BR>
I have however been allowed to start over with a new account on my same credit card... In fact I have two new accounts now that I play simultaneously on both my computers, and I am quickly working out plans for starting my own Guild.  So basically, there is redemption out there for banned people, to a certain degree.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
